%N A057730 Number of free polyominoes (A000105) with perimeter 2n.
%C A057730 Does this include polyominoes with holes? - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Sep 12 2006. Answer from _R. J. Mathar_: Yes! See the illustrations in the links (e.g. perimeter 16, area 7, No 81 or perimeter 16, area 8, No 174).
%C A057730 All lines (sides of cells which are not common to a pair of cells) contribute to the perimeter, including the interior sides of cavities and holes. - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 19 2021
%C A057730 The perimeter of a polyomino is the number of external boundary edges of the square cells constituting it (including the boundary of the holes, but excluding the internal edges, i.e. those between adjacent polyomino cells). This is different from site-perimeter, which is the number of cells adjacent to a polyomino but not belonging to it. Polyominoes are also called "lattice animals", although usually a lattice animal is thought of as consisting of square grid vertices rather than square cells/faces of the same grid; however, for a lattice animal, the term "perimeter" means the number of vertices adjacent to the vertices of the animal but not belonging to it, i.e. the site-perimeter of the corresponding polyomino. For polyominoes with site-perimeter n (equivalently, lattice animals with perimeter n), see A366443. - _Andrei Zabolotskii_, Nov 23 2025
